<article>
    <h1>IN&#xAD;HER&#xAD;ENT BEAUTY: PHO&#xAD;TOG&#xAD;RA&#xAD;PHERS WHO CHANGE HOW WE SEE THE WORLD</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201016/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-16"><time>2020-10-16</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | HAPPENINGS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Sun­daram Tagore Gallery’s lat­est show brings to­gether six pho­tog­ra­phers whose works range from pho­to­jour­nal­ism to fine art photograph­y. The most main­stream name is prob­a­bly pho­to­jour­nal­ist Steve McCurry, whose Afghan Girl pho­to­graph turned him into a house­hold name.</p>
    <p>But it is the women pho­tog­ra­phers who pack the big­gest po­etic punches.</p>
    <p>Karen Knorr’s sur­real pho­to­graphs insert ex­otic an­i­mals into high-res­o­lu­tion im­ages of the ar­chi­tec­tural wonders of Mughal and Ra­jput palaces in In­dia.</p>
    <p>A pea­cock poised as el­e­gantly as a su­per­model in The Queen’s Room (above) is ironic, since this ex­trav­a­gant spec­i­men is prob­a­bly male, chal­leng­ing the tra­di­tion­ally fe­male-gen­dered space.</p>
    <p>Moroc­can pho­tog­ra­pher Lalla Es­saydi’s works also ex­plore gen­dered spa­ces for Arab women.</p>
    <p>Her mod­els, draped in cloth and cov­ered in cal­lig­ra­phy, look straight out of the im­ages at the viewer, re­turn­ing the gaze in a con­tem­po­rary re­but­tal of the Ori­en­tal­ist per­spec­tive.</p>
    <p>Both these pho­tog­ra­phers build dense im­ages of the fan­tas­tic and the sen­sual that are com­pelling and thought-pro­vok­ing.</p>
    <p>The other male pho­tog­ra­phers in­clud­ing Robert Poli­dori and Ed­ward Bur­tyn­sky rather fade in com­par­i­son.</p>
    <p>But there is one stand­out from</p>
    <p>Brazil­ian pho­to­jour­nal­ist Se­bas­tiao Sal­gado – a lyri­cally lush, ro­man­ti­cally Edenic im­age of na­tive Ama­zo­ni­ans ti­tled Scene, taken at a stream near the Marubo Maronal vil­lage in Ama­zonas, Brazil.</p>
    <p>WHERE: Sun­daram Tagore Gallery, 01-05 Gill­man Bar­racks, 5 Lock Road MRT: Labrador Park</p>
    <p>WHEN: Till Nov 21, Tues­days to Fri­days: 10am to 6pm;</p>
    <p>Satur­days: 11am to 7pm</p>
    <p>AD­MIS­SION: Free</p>
    <p>INFO: str.sg/J2zG</p>

